[man] You can get this fringe
metallic skirt $39 at Joe Fresh,

84
00:06:10,658 --> 00:06:12,076
a brand-new store in town.

85
00:06:12,160 --> 00:06:15,872
With price tags that might look
a little bit more appealing to shoppers.

86
00:06:15,955 --> 00:06:17,081
[man]
American consumers,

87
00:06:17,165 --> 00:06:20,793
they really have grasped
the fashion part of H&M,

88
00:06:20,877 --> 00:06:24,005
and we know that American consumers are
very value-oriented.

89
00:06:24,088 --> 00:06:27,008
If you match these two together,
with fashion and value,

90
00:06:27,091 --> 00:06:28,259
then you have a recipe.

91
00:06:28,343 --> 00:06:30,970
[woman]
One Japanese clothing retailer is making

92
00:06:31,054 --> 00:06:33,932
a fast and furious mark here in the U.S.

93
00:06:34,015 --> 00:06:35,642
The price has dropped.

94
00:06:35,725 --> 00:06:40,021
The way of making that product
has completely, completely changed.

95
00:06:40,104 --> 00:06:42,315
And you have to ask yourself
at some point,

96
00:06:42,398 --> 00:06:43,775
"Where does it end?"

97
00:06:43,858 --> 00:06:45,944
The global marketplace is some place

98
00:06:46,027 --> 00:06:48,655
where we export work to have happen

99
00:06:48,738 --> 00:06:52,450
in whatever conditions we want,
and then the products come back to me,

100
00:06:52,534 --> 00:06:55,161
cheap enough to throw away
without thinking about it.

101
00:06:58,081 --> 00:07:00,917
Globalized production basically means

102
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:02,710
that all of the making of goods

103
00:07:02,794 --> 00:07:05,964
has been outsourced to low-cost economies,

104
00:07:06,047 --> 00:07:09,634
particularly where wages are very low
and kept low.

105
00:07:09,717 --> 00:07:13,596
And what that means is that those
at the top of the value chain,

106
00:07:13,680 --> 00:07:16,641
they get to choose
where the products are being made,

107
00:07:16,724 --> 00:07:20,228
and they get to switch if, for example,
one factory says,

108
00:07:20,311 --> 00:07:22,188
"We can't make it that cheap anymore."

109
00:07:22,272 --> 00:07:24,774
The brand will say,
"We're not gonna come to you.

110
00:07:24,858 --> 00:07:27,610
We're gonna switch to another place
which is cheaper."

111
00:07:36,077 --> 00:07:39,247
[man] In the West,
they're using "everyday low price."

112
00:07:39,581 --> 00:07:42,041
So, every day, they're hampering me,

113
00:07:42,125 --> 00:07:44,502
and I'm hampering my workers,
this is how it is.

114
00:07:44,586 --> 00:07:46,838
They're competing.
The stores are competing.

115
00:07:46,921 --> 00:07:50,216
When the stores are coming to us
for an order and negotiating,

116
00:07:50,300 --> 00:07:51,551
they're telling, "Look,

117
00:07:51,634 --> 00:07:55,722
that particular store is selling
this shirt, like, for $5,

118
00:07:55,805 --> 00:07:58,391
so I need to sell it at $4.

119
00:07:58,474 --> 00:08:01,060
So you better squeeze your price."
So we are squeezing.

120
00:08:01,144 --> 00:08:05,064
Then other store is coming and saying,
"Hey, they're selling it at $4?

121
00:08:05,148 --> 00:08:07,483
So the target price is 3.
If you can make that 3,

122
00:08:07,567 --> 00:08:10,153
you're getting business,
otherwise you are not getting."

123
00:08:10,236 --> 00:08:12,780
Because we want that business so badly,

124
00:08:12,864 --> 00:08:15,491
and we don't have other options, okay.

125
00:08:15,575 --> 00:08:18,453
Every time we are trying
to survive, actually.

126
00:08:19,329 --> 00:08:21,289
[Lee]
Ultimately, something's gonna give.

127
00:08:21,372 --> 00:08:23,666
Either the price
of the product has to go up,

128
00:08:23,750 --> 00:08:27,086
or manufacturers have to shut down

129
00:08:27,170 --> 00:08:28,838
or cut corners to make it work.

130
00:08:29,339 --> 00:08:32,050
[narrator] Cutting corners
and disregarding safety measures

131
00:08:32,133 --> 00:08:35,178
had become an accepted part
of doing business in this new model,

132
00:08:35,261 --> 00:08:36,930
until an early morning in April,

133
00:08:37,013 --> 00:08:39,557
when an event just outside
of Dhaka, Bangladesh

134
00:08:39,641 --> 00:08:42,393
brought a hidden side of fashion
to front page news.

135
00:08:42,477 --> 00:08:44,354
State media in Bangladesh say

136
00:08:44,437 --> 00:08:48,024
an eight-story building has collapsed
near the capital of Dhaka,

137
00:08:48,107 --> 00:08:49,776
killing more than 70 people.

138
00:08:49,859 --> 00:08:52,487
[crowd clamoring]
[whistle blowing]

139
00:08:55,990 --> 00:08:59,702
[wailing in foreign language]

140
00:09:02,080 --> 00:09:04,666
[woman 1]
Rescue workers are racing against time,

141
00:09:04,749 --> 00:09:07,210
searching through the rubble,
trying to find

142
00:09:07,293 --> 00:09:09,587
as many survivors as they can.

143
00:09:09,671 --> 00:09:11,089
[man 1]
Hundreds are dead,

144
00:09:11,172 --> 00:09:14,759
hundreds more might still be buried alive,
after officials in Bangladesh say

145
00:09:14,843 --> 00:09:17,720
factory owners ignored
an order to evacuate.

146
00:09:17,804 --> 00:09:22,183
[man 2] Some 400 dead,
hundreds still believed to be missing.

147
00:09:22,267 --> 00:09:26,396
Garment workers in Bangladesh paying
the price for cheap clothing.

148
00:09:26,479 --> 00:09:29,357
[woman 2] A huge crowd has gathered
near the building site,

149
00:09:29,440 --> 00:09:32,902
many of them family members looking
for loved ones,

150
00:09:32,986 --> 00:09:35,697
and they say they can still hear
people screaming

151
00:09:35,780 --> 00:09:39,033
from underneath the rubble,
crying out for help.

152
00:09:39,117 --> 00:09:41,786
Many are simply losing hope.

153
00:09:43,246 --> 00:09:45,248
[speaking in foreign language]

154
00:09:54,424 --> 00:09:55,717
[clears throat]

155
00:10:16,487 --> 00:10:19,574
[Siegle]
Anybody who, like me,

156
00:10:19,657 --> 00:10:23,453
had written about problems
in the supply chain,

157
00:10:23,536 --> 00:10:25,663
particularly for Fast Fashion,

158
00:10:25,747 --> 00:10:27,999
and tried to articulate

159
00:10:28,082 --> 00:10:31,377
how the risk was being carried

160
00:10:31,461 --> 00:10:35,673
by those who are most vulnerable
and the worst paid.

161
00:10:36,299 --> 00:10:39,719
You try to articulate that,
but you could never have envisaged

162
00:10:39,802 --> 00:10:43,056
that there would be such
a catastrophic illustration

163
00:10:43,139 --> 00:10:45,225
of what you were trying to say.

164
00:10:45,308 --> 00:10:49,187
And Rana Plaza, to me,
was like some horror story.

165
00:10:50,104 --> 00:10:52,148
[woman]
Two weeks after the catastrophe

166
00:10:52,232 --> 00:10:56,361
and the death toll now stands
at a staggering 931,

167
00:10:56,444 --> 00:11:00,114
making it the worst
garment-industry disaster in history.

168
00:11:00,198 --> 00:11:04,452
I think one of the most profoundly
impressing things

169
00:11:04,536 --> 00:11:08,540
about the Rana Plaza disaster
was that news

170
00:11:08,623 --> 00:11:12,085
that the workers had already
pointed out to the management

171
00:11:12,168 --> 00:11:13,711
the cracks in the building.

172
00:11:13,795 --> 00:11:15,713
They'd already pointed out

173
00:11:15,797 --> 00:11:18,383
that the building was structurally unsafe,

174
00:11:18,466 --> 00:11:20,760
and yet they'd been forced back in.

175
00:11:20,844 --> 00:11:22,303
[woman]
Survivors are asking

176
00:11:22,387 --> 00:11:24,848
how they could've been forced
to return to work

177
00:11:24,931 --> 00:11:28,476
when management already was aware
of the cracks in the building,

178
00:11:28,560 --> 00:11:31,771
and workers' concerns
on the very day of the collapse.

179
00:11:31,855 --> 00:11:35,108
A lot of clothes in American stores
are made in Bangladesh

180
00:11:35,191 --> 00:11:37,819
by workers who earn about $2 a day.

