and that's incorporated in our way
of working.

967
01:05:01,564 --> 01:05:02,941
[Firth]
How much is it?

968
01:05:03,024 --> 01:05:05,109
And that's not for us to say a sum,

969
01:05:05,193 --> 01:05:07,570
but we do an assessment all the time.

970
01:05:07,654 --> 01:05:08,780
How much is it?

971
01:05:08,863 --> 01:05:13,701
And to make sure that it covers
the basic needs of the workers.

972
01:05:13,785 --> 01:05:16,871
I can show you that later on.

973
01:05:16,955 --> 01:05:19,499
H&M has mastered the model
of Fast Fashion,

974
01:05:19,582 --> 01:05:23,002
becoming the second largest
clothing corporation in history.

975
01:05:23,086 --> 01:05:26,673
With annual revenue
of more than $18 billion,

976
01:05:26,756 --> 01:05:29,175
they are now one
of the largest producers of clothing

977
01:05:29,259 --> 01:05:31,594
in both Bangladesh and Cambodia.

978
01:05:31,970 --> 01:05:35,056
Sadly, along with every other
major retailer I asked,

979
01:05:35,139 --> 01:05:38,810
they declined
all interview requests for this film.

980
01:05:48,820 --> 01:05:50,071
[crowd cheering]

981
01:05:50,154 --> 01:05:52,156
[man yelling in foreign language]

982
01:05:53,575 --> 01:05:56,286
In Cambodia,
garment workers have had enough.

983
01:05:56,369 --> 01:05:57,871
Recently taking to the streets

984
01:05:57,954 --> 01:06:00,915
to demand a minimum wage
increase in the country.

985
01:06:06,212 --> 01:06:09,841
As protests continued, workers were met
with violent crackdowns,

986
01:06:09,924 --> 01:06:13,511
as police began to open fire
with live rounds.

987
01:06:13,595 --> 01:06:15,722
[yelling in foreign language]

988
01:06:15,805 --> 01:06:17,891
[wailing]

989
01:06:17,974 --> 01:06:20,393
[crowd clamoring]
[car horns honking]

990
01:06:25,773 --> 01:06:27,609
[gunfire]

991
01:06:33,281 --> 01:06:35,867
[man] A woman has been killed
and several people injured

992
01:06:35,950 --> 01:06:38,077
in clashes between clothes factory workers

993
01:06:38,161 --> 01:06:40,413
and riot police in Cambodia.

994
01:06:41,247 --> 01:06:42,916
[gunfire]

995
01:06:46,336 --> 01:06:48,213
[crowd clamoring]

996
01:07:03,228 --> 01:07:05,230
[speaking in foreign language]

997
01:07:13,446 --> 01:07:17,825
For two days, Cambodia was a battleground.

998
01:07:17,909 --> 01:07:19,827
The city of Phnom Penh.

999
01:07:19,911 --> 01:07:24,165
The police, the paratroopers
were brought in

1000
01:07:24,249 --> 01:07:28,545
as if there were war
on the streets of Phnom Penh.

1001
01:07:28,628 --> 01:07:32,924
Why? Because workers
in the textile industry

1002
01:07:33,007 --> 01:07:34,634
continued to demand

1003
01:07:34,717 --> 01:07:37,637
a minimum wage of at least $160.

1004
01:07:41,140 --> 01:07:43,142
[woman speaking in foreign language]

1005
01:08:15,842 --> 01:08:21,890
[man] Today is the, uh,
funeral of a factory worker.

1006
01:08:21,973 --> 01:08:25,685
He was beaten to death.

1007
01:08:25,768 --> 01:08:32,025
He had, uh, suffered a lot
before his death this morning.

1008
01:08:32,108 --> 01:08:35,945
And he had done nothing wrong.

1009
01:08:36,029 --> 01:08:40,074
He, among his, uh, fellow workers,

1010
01:08:40,992 --> 01:08:44,954
wanted to have better living conditions.

1011
01:08:45,038 --> 01:08:47,040
[chanting in foreign language]

1012
01:09:05,642 --> 01:09:07,644
[chanting continues]

1013
01:09:11,189 --> 01:09:14,859
We will continue his fight

1014
01:09:15,735 --> 01:09:19,822
so that all Cambodian workers

1015
01:09:20,782 --> 01:09:23,952
will have decent living conditions.

1016
01:09:25,286 --> 01:09:26,788
[interviewer]
Thank you, sir.

1017
01:09:35,463 --> 01:09:38,675
[narrator] The Cambodian government,
like other developing countries

1018
01:09:38,758 --> 01:09:42,387
are desperate for the business
that multinational retailers bring.

1019
01:09:42,971 --> 01:09:45,139
Because of the constant threat
that these brands

1020
01:09:45,223 --> 01:09:47,767
will relocate production
to other low-cost countries,

1021
01:09:47,851 --> 01:09:49,853
the government holds down wages,

1022
01:09:49,936 --> 01:09:53,106
routinely avoiding enforcement
of local labor laws.

1023
01:09:53,189 --> 01:09:56,359
But because the major brands
do not officially employ the workers,

1024
01:09:56,442 --> 01:09:59,112
or own any of the factories
they produce in,

1025
01:09:59,195 --> 01:10:01,155
they're able to profit hugely,

1026
01:10:01,239 --> 01:10:03,616
all while remaining free
of responsibility

1027
01:10:03,700 --> 01:10:06,995
for the effects of poverty wages,
factory disasters,

1028
01:10:07,078 --> 01:10:10,331
and the ongoing violent treatment
of workers.

1029
01:10:10,415 --> 01:10:12,625
The whole system begins to feel

1030
01:10:12,709 --> 01:10:14,627
like a perfectly engineered nightmare

1031
01:10:14,711 --> 01:10:17,338
for the workers trapped inside of it.

1032
01:10:19,549 --> 01:10:24,053
[Mu] You cannot fool us,
and exploit our human resources,

1033
01:10:24,137 --> 01:10:25,805
exploit our workers.

1034
01:10:25,889 --> 01:10:28,391
The workers will continue to rise up.

1035
01:10:28,725 --> 01:10:32,061
I call on the international brands

1036
01:10:32,520 --> 01:10:38,151
to put that struggle into dollars,

1037
01:10:38,234 --> 01:10:41,029
into pounds, into Euros.

1038
01:10:41,821 --> 01:10:45,658
It translates into human capital.

1039
01:10:45,742 --> 01:10:49,954
It translates into social responsibility

1040
01:10:50,038 --> 01:10:51,789
of these big corporations.

1041
01:10:51,873 --> 01:10:55,001
It translates into economic justice.

1042
01:10:55,084 --> 01:10:58,630
When everything is concentrated
on making profits

1043
01:10:58,713 --> 01:11:00,298
for the big corporations,

1044
01:11:00,381 --> 01:11:02,050
what you see is that human rights,

1045
01:11:02,133 --> 01:11:05,678
the environment, workers' rights
get lost all together.

1046
01:11:05,762 --> 01:11:08,556
You see that workers
are increasingly exploited

1047
01:11:08,640 --> 01:11:12,268
because the price of everything
is pushed down and down and down,

1048
01:11:12,352 --> 01:11:16,105
just to satisfy this impulse
to accumulate capital.

1049
01:11:16,189 --> 01:11:18,233
And that's profoundly problematic,

1050
01:11:18,316 --> 01:11:21,027
'cause it leads
to the mass impoverishment

1051
01:11:21,110 --> 01:11:24,322
of hundreds of millions of people
around the world.

1052
01:11:25,740 --> 01:11:29,494
[woman] If you write to these companies,
they'll send you their code of conduct.

1053
01:11:29,577 --> 01:11:33,915
And it's beautiful, and it says,
"Oh, yes, we take responsibility

1054
01:11:33,998 --> 01:11:36,709
for the conditions under which
our product is made,

1055
01:11:36,793 --> 01:11:38,503
you know, the product that you buy.

1056
01:11:38,586 --> 01:11:40,296
All the factories where we produce,

1057
01:11:40,380 --> 01:11:43,925
we require them to respect
the minimum-wage laws,

1058
01:11:44,008 --> 01:11:46,427
you know,
all of the laws of the country,

1059
01:11:46,511 --> 01:11:49,931
to respect women, not to hire children,

1060
01:11:50,014 --> 01:11:52,559
uh, no forced labor,

1061
01:11:52,642 --> 01:11:56,896
um, no excessive overtime hours,"
all that stuff.

1062
01:11:56,980 --> 01:11:58,231
Um...

1063
01:11:58,314 --> 01:12:02,986
But when we submitted a bill
in Congress a few years ago,

1064
01:12:03,069 --> 01:12:05,530
or worked with people to do that,

1065
01:12:05,613 --> 01:12:10,076
we called it "The Decent Working
Conditions and Fair Competition Act,"

1066
01:12:10,159 --> 01:12:12,662
the companies responded in one voice,

1067
01:12:12,745 --> 01:12:15,498
"Oh, no. That would be
an impediment to free trade.

1068
01:12:15,582 --> 01:12:19,627
We can't have rules.
We can't have that."

1069
01:12:19,711 --> 01:12:22,922
They want to keep it
with voluntary codes of conduct.

1070
01:12:23,006 --> 01:12:26,134
You know, they've fought for
and they've won laws

1071
01:12:26,217 --> 01:12:29,971
to protect their stuff
and their interests,

1072
01:12:30,054 --> 01:12:31,639
but what about the workers?

1073
01:12:31,723 --> 01:12:34,267
The workers are left
with voluntary codes of conduct.

1074
01:12:34,350 --> 01:12:38,771
And what we see,
in case, after case, after case,

1075
01:12:38,855 --> 01:12:40,857
is that those voluntary codes of conduct

1076
01:12:40,940 --> 01:12:43,484
are not worth the paper
that they're written on.

1077
01:12:43,568 --> 01:12:46,863
We need to acknowledge,
particularly in the fashion industry,

1078
01:12:46,946 --> 01:12:50,992
that human capital is part
of this miraculous formula.

1079
01:12:51,743 --> 01:12:55,163
Without human capital,
without cheap labor,

1080
01:12:55,246 --> 01:12:57,207
cheap female labor,

1081
01:12:57,290 --> 01:13:00,752
it would not be generating
the profits that it is.

1082
01:13:01,377 --> 01:13:04,589
That needs to be acknowledged,
it needs to be dealt with,

1083
01:13:04,672 --> 01:13:08,343
and those people need to be
rewarded instead of exploited.

1084
01:13:08,426 --> 01:13:10,094
Where is their piece of the pie?

1085
01:13:10,178 --> 01:13:12,388
That's what we constantly
have to ask ourselves.

1086
01:13:12,472 --> 01:13:16,518
Are those buyers immoral?
Or they just don't--? Or are they amoral?

1087
01:13:16,601 --> 01:13:19,729
The system they're working for
and the system that allows companies

1088
01:13:19,812 --> 01:13:21,022
to do this is amoral.

1089
01:13:21,105 --> 01:13:23,858
The individuals concerned
are simply products of that system

1090
01:13:23,942 --> 01:13:26,569
and having to drive it through
to its logical conclusion.

1091
01:13:26,653 --> 01:13:29,989
What we need to do is change the way
those companies operate.

1092
01:13:30,698 --> 01:13:33,409
Operating within a system
that only measures profit,

1093
01:13:33,493 --> 01:13:35,912
companies have little incentive
to do anything

1094
01:13:35,995 --> 01:13:39,123
other than to make this quarter
better than the last.

1095
01:13:39,207 --> 01:13:42,252
No matter what damage
is caused along the way.

1096
01:13:42,335 --> 01:13:45,129
As corporations that make up
the global fashion industry,

1097
01:13:45,213 --> 01:13:47,674
major brands, as well as seed
and chemical companies,

1098
01:13:47,757 --> 01:13:51,803
are growing today to reach
unprecedented global size and power.

1099
01:13:51,886 --> 01:13:55,515
This mandate for profit at all cost
is beginning to stand

1100
01:13:55,598 --> 01:13:58,852
in direct opposition
to the values that we share.

1101
01:13:59,936 --> 01:14:01,521
Richard Wolff is an economist,

1102
01:14:01,604 --> 01:14:05,024
who after graduating from Harvard,
Stanford and Yale,

1103
01:14:05,108 --> 01:14:09,320
became convinced that the real problem
is within this system itself.

1104
01:14:09,404 --> 01:14:13,324
So, America became a peculiar country.

1105
01:14:13,408 --> 01:14:16,536
You could criticize the education system
to make the schools better.

1106
01:14:16,619 --> 01:14:20,623
You could criticize the transportation
system to make that work better.

1107
01:14:20,707 --> 01:14:23,751
But you couldn't criticize
the economic system.

1108
01:14:23,835 --> 01:14:25,962
That got a free pass.

1109
01:14:26,045 --> 01:14:27,672
You couldn't criticize, just--

1110
01:14:27,755 --> 01:14:30,717
And if you don't criticize something
for 50 years,

1111
01:14:30,800 --> 01:14:33,595
it rots, it goes to seed.

1112
01:14:33,678 --> 01:14:35,555
One of the ways a healthy society works

1113
01:14:35,638 --> 01:14:39,642
is it subjects its component systems
to criticism,

1114
01:14:39,726 --> 01:14:42,270
so that we can debate it,
and hopefully fix it,

1115
01:14:42,353 --> 01:14:44,272
or improve it or do better.

1116
01:14:44,355 --> 01:14:47,066
Capitalism couldn't be questioned.

1117
01:14:47,150 --> 01:14:48,318
Capitalism is the reason

1118
01:14:48,401 --> 01:14:51,154
the fashion industry looks
as it does today.

1119
01:14:51,237 --> 01:14:54,991
It's the reason why workers
in Bangladesh are paid so little.

1120
01:14:55,074 --> 01:14:57,869
Because if you're operating
in a capitalist system,

1121
01:14:57,952 --> 01:15:00,997
the main thing you have to do
is create profit

1122
01:15:01,080 --> 01:15:04,542
and you have to create more profit
than your competitors.

1123
01:15:04,626 --> 01:15:06,628
And this is what drives companies

1124
01:15:06,711 --> 01:15:09,714
to push wages down and down and down.

1125
01:15:09,797 --> 01:15:13,885
But companies don't go--
Like fashion retailers

1126
01:15:13,968 --> 01:15:18,640
don't go to places like Bangladesh,
for any other reason except

1127
01:15:18,723 --> 01:15:21,184
they can get the cheapest labor possible.

1128
01:15:21,267 --> 01:15:23,853
There's no collective rights
in Bangladesh,

1129
01:15:23,937 --> 01:15:25,647
there's no trade union rights,

1130
01:15:25,730 --> 01:15:27,690
there's a very, very low minimum wage,

1131
01:15:27,774 --> 01:15:30,693
there's no, like, maternity benefits,
there's no pensions,

1132
01:15:30,777 --> 01:15:33,363
that is why the fashion industry
is in Bangladesh

1133
01:15:33,446 --> 01:15:36,366
because it can reap the biggest profits
out of those people

1134
01:15:36,449 --> 01:15:38,493
that are making the clothes for them.

1135
01:15:38,576 --> 01:15:41,829
Before you can solve a problem,
you have to admit you got one

1136
01:15:41,913 --> 01:15:44,374
and before we're gonna fix
an economic system

1137
01:15:44,457 --> 01:15:47,418
that's working this way,
and producing such tensions

1138
01:15:47,502 --> 01:15:51,256
and inequalities and strains
on our community,

1139
01:15:51,339 --> 01:15:55,176
we have to face the real scope
of the problem we have

1140
01:15:55,260 --> 01:15:58,054
and that's with the system as a whole.

1141
01:15:58,137 --> 01:15:59,430
And at the very least,

1142
01:15:59,514 --> 01:16:02,141
we have to open up
a national debate about it,

1143
01:16:02,225 --> 01:16:05,728
and at the most, I think
we have to think long and hard

1144
01:16:05,812 --> 01:16:08,314
about alternative systems
that might work better.

1145
01:16:08,398 --> 01:16:11,943
[Hilary] For the environment,
the great threat is that capital

1146
01:16:12,026 --> 01:16:16,322
must continue to expand infinitely
in order to survive.

1147
01:16:16,406 --> 01:16:20,201
It can't have any limits
on its expansion and its growth.

1148
01:16:20,285 --> 01:16:22,871
The natural world
clearly does have limits.

1149
01:16:22,954 --> 01:16:26,541
There are very defined limits
to how much the world can sustain

1150
01:16:26,624 --> 01:16:29,043
in terms of production,
in terms of trade,

1151
01:16:29,127 --> 01:16:31,462
in terms of transport and distribution.

1152
01:16:31,546 --> 01:16:34,090
And it's quite clear
that we've already overstepped

1153
01:16:34,174 --> 01:16:37,260
a lot of those limits, which is why
you're seeing such stress

1154
01:16:37,343 --> 01:16:39,846
in the natural world at the moment.

1155
01:16:39,929 --> 01:16:43,391
[Hoskins] The system we live in isn't one
that most people want to live in.

1156
01:16:43,474 --> 01:16:46,519
I think it's a system that makes
most people very unhappy,

1157
01:16:46,603 --> 01:16:49,939
and I don't think people want to live
on a slowly dying planet

1158
01:16:50,023 --> 01:16:52,650
or to be exploiting, um, you know,
their neighbors.

1159
01:16:52,734 --> 01:16:57,030
So, I think we need
huge systemic change.

1160
01:16:57,113 --> 01:16:59,699
[Wolff]
If you don't change the system,

1161
01:16:59,782 --> 01:17:02,327
you're leaving intact

1162
01:17:02,410 --> 01:17:05,747
the decision-making of these enterprises,

1163
01:17:05,830 --> 01:17:09,083
which means a small group
of executives and shareholders

1164
01:17:09,167 --> 01:17:11,461
are gonna be working
in the same system,

1165
01:17:11,544 --> 01:17:14,589
subject to the same pattern
of rewards and punishments,

1166
01:17:14,672 --> 01:17:18,218
which will sooner or later
make them reimpose,

1167
01:17:18,301 --> 01:17:19,928
there or elsewhere,

1168
01:17:20,011 --> 01:17:22,180
the very conditions
you're fighting against.

1169
01:17:22,263 --> 01:17:26,142
So, stop this stuff about improving
their conditions,

1170
01:17:26,226 --> 01:17:29,896
deal with the system,
or else you're not serious.

1171
01:17:29,979 --> 01:17:33,399
[Kasser] Our economic system
is one of consumer capitalism,

1172
01:17:33,483 --> 01:17:37,987
and that's why the government needs
to have consumption

1173
01:17:38,071 --> 01:17:40,031
at very high levels, um,

1174
01:17:40,114 --> 01:17:42,075
and why, of course, the corporations do,

1175
01:17:42,158 --> 01:17:45,203
and why at some level
most people then buy into it.

1176
01:17:45,286 --> 01:17:48,831
I can't tell you the number of people
I talked to who say, "Well,

1177
01:17:48,915 --> 01:17:52,877
but if we became less materialistic
our economy would tank."

1178
01:17:52,961 --> 01:17:57,966
Well, they're right in some level,
because our economy is

1179
01:17:58,049 --> 01:18:03,513
based on materialism,
it's based on these kinds of values.

1180
01:18:03,596 --> 01:18:06,224
That's what it needs
in order to survive.

1181
01:18:06,307 --> 01:18:08,768
That's part of the fuel that it needs.

1182
01:18:09,394 --> 01:18:11,938
The problem is that comes
at a really high price.

1183
01:18:12,021 --> 01:18:15,358
 Black Friday's here
Can we go please? 

1184
01:18:15,441 --> 01:18:18,403
 Go, go, go, go, go
Shop, shop, shop, shop 

1185
