than on any other, uh, day of the year.

1198
01:18:53,104 --> 01:18:58,109
Nation, this orgy of Christmas shopping
proves America is back!

1199
01:18:58,193 --> 01:18:59,986
We are once again... Yes!

1200
01:19:00,069 --> 01:19:01,571
[audience cheering]

1201
01:19:01,654 --> 01:19:03,156
Oh, yes!

1202
01:19:03,865 --> 01:19:07,869
We are once again
spending money we don't have

1203
01:19:07,952 --> 01:19:10,830
on things we don't need
to give to people we don't like.

1204
01:19:10,914 --> 01:19:12,916
[audience cheering]

1205
01:19:12,999 --> 01:19:14,000
Yeah.

1206
01:19:14,083 --> 01:19:18,713
[chanting]
U.S.A.! U.S.A.! U.S.A.!

1207
01:19:19,797 --> 01:19:21,508
[woman screaming]

1208
01:19:24,469 --> 01:19:25,803
[man]
Oh, my God!

1209
01:19:36,564 --> 01:19:38,566
[inaudible dialogue]

1210
01:20:26,114 --> 01:20:28,116
[crowd clamoring]

1211
01:21:07,280 --> 01:21:09,324
[speaking in foreign language]

1212
01:21:25,548 --> 01:21:27,425
[speaking in foreign language]

1213
01:21:31,262 --> 01:21:33,139
[Akhter speaking in foreign language]

1214
01:22:52,010 --> 01:22:56,014
[Pepper] I grew up on a farm,
married a guy that grew up on a farm,

1215
01:22:56,097 --> 01:22:59,684
and, uh, those of us living
on the farm live there.

1216
01:22:59,767 --> 01:23:04,230
It needs to be safe for us, too.
The new chemicals that are coming out,

1217
01:23:04,314 --> 01:23:08,902
and the intensity of the use,
was just continuing to increase.

1218
01:23:08,985 --> 01:23:13,323
And, um, then in 2005,

1219
01:23:13,781 --> 01:23:15,158
um...

1220
01:23:15,241 --> 01:23:18,077
Terry started having some loss
of fine motor skills,

1221
01:23:18,161 --> 01:23:20,288
and this and that,
and come to find out

1222
01:23:20,371 --> 01:23:24,083
he had a glioblastoma multiforme,
Stage 4 brain tumor,

1223
01:23:25,126 --> 01:23:28,796
and, uh, at the prime age
of 47 years old.

1224
01:23:29,339 --> 01:23:31,925
And, uh, he died at the age of 50.

1225
01:23:32,008 --> 01:23:34,802
They gave us six months,
we had two-and-a-half years,

1226
01:23:34,886 --> 01:23:38,056
and the brain surgeon
that worked on him--

1227
01:23:38,139 --> 01:23:44,145
Lubbock has got huge cancer clinics
and a medical hub.

1228
01:23:44,229 --> 01:23:47,482
We didn't have to go someplace else
to have a brain tumor surgery.

1229
01:23:47,565 --> 01:23:51,152
We were able to stay right here
because he does so many of them.

1230
01:23:51,236 --> 01:23:55,490
He said that these kinds of tumors
are found in men, aged 45-65,

1231
01:23:55,573 --> 01:24:00,495
that work in the agricultural industry
or the oil field.

1232
01:24:00,578 --> 01:24:03,706
And so while I don't have a smoking gun
and the blood tests that say

1233
01:24:03,790 --> 01:24:08,878
the use of, uh, cotton chemicals,
agricultural chemicals,

1234
01:24:08,962 --> 01:24:11,548
directly led to my husband's death,

1235
01:24:11,631 --> 01:24:14,592
there's just too many linkages
with his father's death.

1236
01:24:14,676 --> 01:24:16,678
Growing up
on a chemically-intensive farm,

1237
01:24:16,761 --> 01:24:19,597
we live in the middle
of 3.6 million acres of cotton

1238
01:24:19,681 --> 01:24:21,391
that use a lot of chemicals.

1239
01:24:21,474 --> 01:24:24,853
And so, at that point in time,

1240
01:24:24,936 --> 01:24:27,647
organic was no longer important to me,

1241
01:24:28,439 --> 01:24:30,024
it was imperative.

1242
01:24:30,108 --> 01:24:32,235
It's imperative
that we change agriculture.

1243
01:24:32,318 --> 01:24:35,864
It's imperative, if we're talking
about the long-term sustainability

1244
01:24:35,947 --> 01:24:38,825
and well-being
of our lives on this planet

1245
01:24:38,908 --> 01:24:40,743
and our children's lives on the planet,

1246
01:24:40,827 --> 01:24:43,580
that we have to change.

1247
01:25:05,685 --> 01:25:08,062
[Minney] This is the beginning
of a turning point

1248
01:25:08,146 --> 01:25:11,065
not just for, you know,
a responsible way of doing fashion,

1249
01:25:11,149 --> 01:25:14,861
but for a new way of doing capitalism,
for a new way of doing economics.

1250
01:25:15,486 --> 01:25:20,450
I'm sure that we will see
a significant change

1251
01:25:20,533 --> 01:25:22,285
over the next ten years.

1252
01:25:22,368 --> 01:25:25,413
Um, whether it's in time or not
is another question.

1253
01:25:27,582 --> 01:25:29,167
[Kasser]
Martin Luther King Jr.,

1254
01:25:29,250 --> 01:25:31,461
at a speech in a Brooklyn church,
he said

1255
01:25:31,544 --> 01:25:35,256
that what America needed was
a revolution of values.

1256
01:25:35,340 --> 01:25:38,426
It needed to stop
treating people like things.

1257
01:25:38,510 --> 01:25:41,513
It needed to stop treating
people in ways

1258
01:25:41,596 --> 01:25:43,348
that were just about profit.

1259
01:25:43,431 --> 01:25:47,560
But instead to treat people
in a real and human way.

1260
01:25:48,228 --> 01:25:51,397
[Wolff] My God,
we can do better than this.

1261
01:25:51,481 --> 01:25:56,653
If what we want is to spread,
as I would argue we do,

1262
01:25:56,736 --> 01:26:00,823
spread industry around the world,
not concentrated in one place.

1263
01:26:00,907 --> 01:26:04,994
Let the benefits be shared globally.

1264
01:26:05,078 --> 01:26:10,667
Then let's do that in an orderly,
reasonable, careful way.

1265
01:26:10,750 --> 01:26:13,878
[Shiva] We need to recognize
that capital is just money.

1266
01:26:13,962 --> 01:26:15,547
Money is a means,

1267
01:26:15,630 --> 01:26:18,508
and people should be accountable
for how it's used.

1268
01:26:18,591 --> 01:26:23,555
We need to celebrate the creative power
of human beings.

1269
01:26:23,638 --> 01:26:27,559
And we need to talk of creative work,
we must stop talking about labor.

1270
01:26:27,642 --> 01:26:32,188
We need to look at the land
as not a commodity,

1271
01:26:32,689 --> 01:26:34,983
to be speculated on and traded,

1272
01:26:35,066 --> 01:26:38,862
but as the very basis of our life,
as Mother Earth.

1273
01:26:38,945 --> 01:26:42,156
[Siegle] You change all consumers
into activists,

1274
01:26:42,240 --> 01:26:44,284
all consumers asking ethical questions,

1275
01:26:44,367 --> 01:26:47,704
all consumers asking
quite simple questions about

1276
01:26:47,787 --> 01:26:49,414
where their clothes are from,

1277
01:26:49,497 --> 01:26:53,501
all consumers saying, "I'm sorry,
it's not acceptable for someone to die

1278
01:26:53,585 --> 01:26:55,170
in the course of a working day."

1279
01:26:55,253 --> 01:26:58,631
We can't just roll over and say,
"Yes, have it. Do what you like."

1280
01:26:58,715 --> 01:27:01,134
It's too important,
it's too significant an industry.

1281
01:27:01,217 --> 01:27:05,722
It has too much impact and effect
on millions of people worldwide

1282
01:27:05,805 --> 01:27:07,724
and common resources.

1283
01:27:13,730 --> 01:27:16,065
[narrator] Will we continue
to search for happiness

1284
01:27:16,149 --> 01:27:18,193
in the consumption of things?

1285
01:27:18,985 --> 01:27:22,572
Will we be satisfied with a system
that makes us feel rich,

1286
01:27:22,655 --> 01:27:25,658
while leaving our world
so desperately poor?

1287
01:27:25,742 --> 01:27:27,535
Will we continue to turn a blind eye

1288
01:27:27,619 --> 01:27:30,038
to the lives of those behind our clothes?

1289
01:27:30,121 --> 01:27:33,625
Or will this be a turning point,
a new chapter in our story,

1290
01:27:33,708 --> 01:27:37,045
when together,
we begin to make a real change,

1291
01:27:37,128 --> 01:27:42,133
as we remember that everything we wear
was touched by human hands?

1292
01:27:42,717 --> 01:27:45,678
In the midst of all the challenges
facing us today,

1293
01:27:45,762 --> 01:27:47,889
for all the problems
that feel bigger than us

1294
01:27:47,972 --> 01:27:49,807
and beyond our control,

1295
01:27:49,891 --> 01:27:51,809
maybe we could start here

1296
01:27:51,893 --> 01:27:53,520
with clothing.